# Application Layer

Orchestrates the domain to fulfill use cases. Depends only on `domain`.
MUST NOT import `infrastructure` or `presentation`.

## Structure

```
application/
├── usecase/   # One class per use case
├── dto/       # Commands (input) + Responses (output)
└── handler/   # Domain event handlers
```

## Use cases (`usecase/`)

- **One use case = one class** with a single public entry method (`execute`/`handle`).
- Named after the business action: `CreateUserUseCase`, `ConfirmAccountUseCase`.
- Receive domain ports via constructor injection (depend on interfaces, not implementations).
- Coordinate domain objects + ports; contain no framework logic and no business
  invariants that belong in the domain.

```java
public class CreateUserUseCase {
    private final UserRepository userRepository;
    private final PasswordHasher passwordHasher;
    private final EventPublisher eventPublisher;

    public CreateUserUseCase(UserRepository userRepository,
                             PasswordHasher passwordHasher,
                             EventPublisher eventPublisher) {
        this.userRepository = userRepository;
        this.passwordHasher = passwordHasher;
        this.eventPublisher = eventPublisher;
    }

    public UserResponse execute(CreateUserCommand command) {
        if (userRepository.findByEmail(new Email(command.email())).isPresent())
            throw new EmailAlreadyInUseException(command.email());
        var user = User.register(command.name(),
                                 new Email(command.email()),
                                 passwordHasher.hash(command.password()));
        var saved = userRepository.save(user);
        eventPublisher.publish(new UserRegisteredEvent(saved.id()));
        return UserResponse.from(saved);
    }
}
```

## DTOs (`dto/`)

- **Commands** = use case input (`CreateUserCommand`, `LoginCommand`).
- **Responses** = use case output (`UserResponse`). Decouple callers from domain models.
- Prefer Java `record`s. Never expose domain entities directly across the boundary.

## Event handlers (`handler/`)

- React to domain events: `UserRegisteredEventHandler` triggers e.g. sending a welcome email
  via an application port. Keep handlers thin; delegate to use cases/ports.

## Ports

- If a use case needs an external capability, depend on an **interface** (defined in
  `domain` or `application`). The concrete adapter lives in `infrastructure`.
- Transaction boundaries belong here (the use case), not in the domain.
